Note:
AArch64 Calling Convention Implementation (AAPCS64)

Implements the ARM Architecture Procedure Call Standard for 64-bit (AAPCS64) calling
convention used on all AArch64 platforms (Linux, macOS/iOS, Android, Windows on ARM).

This file performs the following tasks:
- Defines AAPCS64 calling convention data structures for argument passing and register usage
- Creates convention instances with correct register maps for AArch64
- Classifies function arguments as INTEGER or FLOATING class per AAPCS64 rules
- Maps argument indices to physical registers or stack positions
- Computes stack space requirements for spilled arguments
- Provides callee-saved and caller-saved register lists per AAPCS64
- Computes stack frame adjustments ensuring 16-byte alignment

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Correct calling convention handling is required for interoperability with C libraries and OS APIs on AArch64
- AAPCS64 differs from x86_64 ABIs in register count, alignment rules, and frame layout
- Proper frame alignment prevents alignment faults on AArch64 (strict alignment enforcement)

AArch64 Register Map:
  GPRs: X0-X30 (64-bit), W0-W30 (32-bit lower half)
    X0-X7   (IDs 0-7):   Integer argument and return registers
    X8      (ID 8):       Indirect result location register (struct return)
    X9-X15  (IDs 9-15):   Caller-saved temporaries
    X16     (ID 16):      Intra-procedure-call scratch (IP0)
    X17     (ID 17):      Intra-procedure-call scratch (IP1)
    X18     (ID 18):      Platform register (reserved on some OSes)
    X19-X28 (IDs 19-28):  Callee-saved registers
    X29     (ID 29):      Frame pointer (FP)
    X30     (ID 30):      Link register (LR)
    SP:                   Stack pointer (not a GPR, accessed separately)
    XZR:                  Zero register (reads as 0, writes discarded)

  FPRs: V0-V31 (128-bit NEON/FP), D0-D31 (64-bit float), S0-S31 (32-bit float)
    V0-V7   (IDs 32-39):  Float argument and return registers
    V8-V15  (IDs 40-47):  Callee-saved (lower 64 bits only, D8-D15)
    V16-V31 (IDs 48-63):  Caller-saved temporaries

Dependencies:
- Imports machine_code_interface.runa for common constants and types
- Imports layout.runa for memory allocation
- Imports list.runa for register list construction
:End Note

Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Argument Classification Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
AAPCS64 classifies arguments into two primary classes for register assignment:
- INTEGER: All non-floating-point types (integers, booleans, pointers, struct pointers)
  are passed in general-purpose registers X0-X7.
- FLOATING: Float and Float64 types are passed in SIMD/FP registers V0-V7
  (using D0-D7 for doubles, S0-S7 for singles).
- MEMORY: Arguments that do not fit in registers are passed on the stack.
- NO_CLASS: Void or zero-size types that consume no argument slot.

Unlike x86_64 System V where integer and float arguments track independent indices,
AAPCS64 also tracks them independently: the first integer argument goes in X0
regardless of how many float arguments preceded it, and vice versa.
@End Reasoning

Constant ARG_CLASS_INTEGER as Integer is 0     Note: Passed in GPR X0-X7
Constant ARG_CLASS_FLOATING as Integer is 1    Note: Passed in V0-V7 (SIMD/FP register)
Constant ARG_CLASS_MEMORY as Integer is 2      Note: Passed on the stack
Constant ARG_CLASS_NO_CLASS as Integer is 3    Note: Void or zero-size, no slot consumed

Note: Calling Convention Identifier
Constant CALLING_CONV_AAPCS64 as Integer is 2  Note: AAPCS64 (distinct from System V = 0, Win64 = 1)

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AArch64 Register ID Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Physical register IDs for AArch64. GPRs are numbered 0-30 matching the hardware
register file (X0-X30). FPRs (NEON/SIMD) are numbered starting at 32 so they
occupy a distinct ID range from GPRs. This mirrors the x86_64 convention where
GPRs are 0-15 and XMMs are 16-31.

SP and XZR are special: SP is not a numbered GPR (it shares encoding 31 with XZR
in the hardware but they are distinguished by instruction context). We assign
them IDs 31 and 64 respectively for internal tracking, though they rarely appear
in register allocation since SP is managed by prologue/epilogue and XZR is not
allocatable.
@End Reasoning

Constant REG_X0 as Integer is 0
Constant REG_X1 as Integer is 1
Constant REG_X2 as Integer is 2
Constant REG_X3 as Integer is 3
Constant REG_X4 as Integer is 4
Constant REG_X5 as Integer is 5
Constant REG_X6 as Integer is 6
Constant REG_X7 as Integer is 7
Constant REG_X8 as Integer is 8
Constant REG_X9 as Integer is 9
Constant REG_X10 as Integer is 10
Constant REG_X11 as Integer is 11
Constant REG_X12 as Integer is 12
Constant REG_X13 as Integer is 13
Constant REG_X14 as Integer is 14
Constant REG_X15 as Integer is 15
Constant REG_X16 as Integer is 16   Note: IP0 (intra-procedure-call scratch)
Constant REG_X17 as Integer is 17   Note: IP1 (intra-procedure-call scratch)
Constant REG_X18 as Integer is 18   Note: Platform register (reserved on some OSes)
Constant REG_X19 as Integer is 19
Constant REG_X20 as Integer is 20
Constant REG_X21 as Integer is 21
Constant REG_X22 as Integer is 22
Constant REG_X23 as Integer is 23
Constant REG_X24 as Integer is 24
Constant REG_X25 as Integer is 25
Constant REG_X26 as Integer is 26
Constant REG_X27 as Integer is 27
Constant REG_X28 as Integer is 28
Constant REG_X29 as Integer is 29   Note: Frame pointer (FP)
Constant REG_X30 as Integer is 30   Note: Link register (LR)
Constant REG_SP as Integer is 31    Note: Stack pointer
Constant REG_XZR as Integer is 65   Note: Zero register (not allocatable)

Note: FPR/NEON register IDs (offset by 32 from hardware number)
Constant REG_V0 as Integer is 32
Constant REG_V1 as Integer is 33
Constant REG_V2 as Integer is 34
Constant REG_V3 as Integer is 35
Constant REG_V4 as Integer is 36
Constant REG_V5 as Integer is 37
