Note: ============================================================================
Note: CallingConventionInfo Type Definition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
CallingConventionInfo encapsulates all data needed to generate correct function prologues,
epilogues, call sequences, and register allocation constraints for AAPCS64.

Structure layout (12 fields, 96 bytes):
  offset  0: convention_id          - CALLING_CONV_AAPCS64
  offset  8: int_arg_registers      - List pointer: GPRs X0-X7 for integer arguments
  offset 16: float_arg_registers    - List pointer: V0-V7 for floating-point arguments
  offset 24: int_arg_count          - Number of GPRs available (8 for AAPCS64)
  offset 32: float_arg_count        - Number of FPRs available (8 for AAPCS64)
  offset 40: return_register        - GPR for integer return value (X0)
  offset 48: float_return_register  - FPR for float return value (V0/D0/S0)
  offset 56: callee_saved_registers - List pointer: registers the callee must preserve
  offset 64: caller_saved_registers - List pointer: registers the caller must save
  offset 72: stack_alignment        - Required stack alignment in bytes (16 for AAPCS64)
  offset 80: red_zone_size          - Red zone below SP (0 for AAPCS64 on Linux; 128 on Darwin)
  offset 88: shadow_space_size      - No shadow space in AAPCS64 (0)
@End Reasoning

Type called "CallingConventionInfo":
    convention_id as Integer           Note: CALLING_CONV_AAPCS64
    int_arg_registers as Integer       Note: List of GPR register IDs for integer args (X0-X7)
    float_arg_registers as Integer     Note: List of V register IDs for float args (V0-V7)
    int_arg_count as Integer           Note: Number of integer argument registers (8)
    float_arg_count as Integer         Note: Number of float argument registers (8)
    return_register as Integer         Note: Integer return register ID (X0 = 0)
    float_return_register as Integer   Note: Float return register ID (V0 = 32)
    callee_saved_registers as Integer  Note: List of callee-saved register IDs
    caller_saved_registers as Integer  Note: List of caller-saved register IDs
    stack_alignment as Integer         Note: Stack alignment requirement in bytes (16)
    red_zone_size as Integer           Note: Red zone size in bytes below SP
    shadow_space_size as Integer       Note: Shadow space size (0 for AAPCS64)
End Type

Note: Size: 12 fields * 8 bytes = 96 bytes per CallingConventionInfo

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AAPCS64 Convention Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Creates a fully populated CallingConventionInfo for the AAPCS64 calling convention.

AAPCS64 key characteristics:
- 8 integer argument registers: X0-X7
- 8 floating-point argument registers: V0-V7 (D0-D7 for doubles, S0-S7 for singles)
- Integer and float argument counts tracked independently (same as System V x86_64)
- Return values in X0 (integer) or V0/D0/S0 (float)
- X8 used as indirect result location register for large struct returns
- Callee-saved GPRs: X19-X28
- Callee-saved FPRs: V8-V15 (only lower 64 bits, D8-D15)
- Frame pointer X29 and link register X30 are callee-saved by convention
- X16, X17 are intra-procedure-call temporaries (may be clobbered by linker veneers)
- X18 is the platform register (reserved on Darwin, available on Linux)
- 16-byte stack alignment at all times (AAPCS64 requires SP to be 16-byte aligned at public interface)
- No shadow space
- Red zone: 0 on Linux, 128 on Darwin (macOS/iOS)

The target_os parameter controls red zone size: Darwin gets 128 bytes, all others get 0.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_aapcs64_convention" that takes target_os as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate CallingConventionInfo structure (96 bytes)
    Let info be Layout.allocate(96)
    If info is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set convention identifier
    __store(info, 0, CALLING_CONV_AAPCS64)

    Note: Build integer argument register list: X0(0) through X7(7)
    Let int_regs be List.list_create(8)
    If int_regs is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    List.list_append(int_regs, 0)    Note: X0 minus 1st integer arg divided by return value
    List.list_append(int_regs, 1)    Note: X1 minus 2nd integer arg divided by return value (128-bit)
    List.list_append(int_regs, 2)    Note: X2 minus 3rd integer arg
    List.list_append(int_regs, 3)    Note: X3 minus 4th integer arg
    List.list_append(int_regs, 4)    Note: X4 minus 5th integer arg
    List.list_append(int_regs, 5)    Note: X5 minus 6th integer arg
    List.list_append(int_regs, 6)    Note: X6 minus 7th integer arg
    List.list_append(int_regs, 7)    Note: X7 minus 8th integer arg
    __store(info, 8, int_regs)

    Note: Build float argument register list: V0(32) through V7(39)
    Let float_regs be List.list_create(8)
    If float_regs is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    List.list_append(float_regs, 32)  Note: V0/D0/S0 minus 1st float arg divided by return value
    List.list_append(float_regs, 33)  Note: V1/D1/S1 minus 2nd float arg
    List.list_append(float_regs, 34)  Note: V2/D2/S2 minus 3rd float arg
    List.list_append(float_regs, 35)  Note: V3/D3/S3 minus 4th float arg
    List.list_append(float_regs, 36)  Note: V4/D4/S4 minus 5th float arg
    List.list_append(float_regs, 37)  Note: V5/D5/S5 minus 6th float arg
    List.list_append(float_regs, 38)  Note: V6/D6/S6 minus 7th float arg
    List.list_append(float_regs, 39)  Note: V7/D7/S7 minus 8th float arg
    __store(info, 16, float_regs)

    Note: Set argument register counts
    __store(info, 24, 8)   Note: 8 integer argument registers (X0-X7)
    __store(info, 32, 8)   Note: 8 float argument registers (V0-V7)

    Note: Set return registers
    __store(info, 40, 0)   Note: X0(0) for integer returns
    __store(info, 48, 32)  Note: V0(32) for float returns

    Note: Build callee-saved register list:
    Note: GPRs: X19(19)-X28(28), X29(29)/FP, X30(30)/LR
    Note: FPRs: V8(40)-V15(47) (lower 64 bits only, D8-D15)
    Let callee_saved be List.list_create(24)
    If callee_saved is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 19)  Note: X19
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 20)  Note: X20
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 21)  Note: X21
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 22)  Note: X22
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 23)  Note: X23
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 24)  Note: X24
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 25)  Note: X25
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 26)  Note: X26
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 27)  Note: X27
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 28)  Note: X28
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 29)  Note: X29 (FP minus frame pointer)
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 30)  Note: X30 (LR minus link register)
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 40)  Note: V8 (D8 minus lower 64 bits callee-saved)
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 41)  Note: V9 (D9)
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 42)  Note: V10 (D10)
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 43)  Note: V11 (D11)
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 44)  Note: V12 (D12)
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 45)  Note: V13 (D13)
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 46)  Note: V14 (D14)
    List.list_append(callee_saved, 47)  Note: V15 (D15)
    __store(info, 56, callee_saved)

    Note: Build caller-saved register list:
    Note: GPRs: X0(0)-X15(15), X16(16)/IP0, X17(17)/IP1, X18(18)/platform
    Note: FPRs: V0(32)-V7(39), V16(48)-V31(63)
    Let caller_saved be List.list_create(40)
    If caller_saved is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 0)   Note: X0
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 1)   Note: X1
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 2)   Note: X2
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 3)   Note: X3
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 4)   Note: X4
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 5)   Note: X5
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 6)   Note: X6
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 7)   Note: X7
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 8)   Note: X8 (indirect result)
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 9)   Note: X9
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 10)  Note: X10
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 11)  Note: X11
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 12)  Note: X12
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 13)  Note: X13
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 14)  Note: X14
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 15)  Note: X15
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 16)  Note: X16 (IP0)
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 17)  Note: X17 (IP1)
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 18)  Note: X18 (platform register)
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 32)  Note: V0
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 33)  Note: V1
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 34)  Note: V2
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 35)  Note: V3
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 36)  Note: V4
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 37)  Note: V5
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 38)  Note: V6
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 39)  Note: V7
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 48)  Note: V16
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 49)  Note: V17
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 50)  Note: V18
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 51)  Note: V19
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 52)  Note: V20
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 53)  Note: V21
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 54)  Note: V22
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 55)  Note: V23
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 56)  Note: V24
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 57)  Note: V25
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 58)  Note: V26
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 59)  Note: V27
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 60)  Note: V28
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 61)  Note: V29
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 62)  Note: V30
    List.list_append(caller_saved, 63)  Note: V31
    __store(info, 64, caller_saved)

    Note: Set stack parameters
    __store(info, 72, 16)   Note: 16-byte stack alignment (mandatory in AAPCS64)
    Note: Red zone depends on target OS: 128 bytes on Darwin, 0 on Linux and others
    If target_os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_DARWIN:
        __store(info, 80, 128)  Note: 128-byte red zone on macOS/iOS
    Otherwise:
        __store(info, 80, 0)    Note: No red zone on Linux/Android/bare-metal
    End If
    __store(info, 88, 0)    Note: No shadow space in AAPCS64

    Return info
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Argument Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Classifies a function argument based on its HIR type information to determine whether
it should be passed in a general-purpose register (INTEGER class) or a SIMD/FP register
(FLOATING class) under AAPCS64.

The classification follows the type_kind encoding used throughout the compiler:
  type_kind 0 = Void     -> ARG_CLASS_NO_CLASS
  type_kind 1 = Integer  -> ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
  type_kind 2 = Float    -> ARG_CLASS_FLOATING
  type_kind 3 = String   -> ARG_CLASS_INTEGER (String is a pointer, passed in GPR)
  type_kind 4 = Boolean  -> ARG_CLASS_INTEGER

All pointer types, struct pointers, array pointers, and reference types are passed as
INTEGER class because they are 8-byte pointer values on AArch64.

The convention parameter is accepted for future extensibility but currently AAPCS64
is the only AArch64 convention.
@End Reasoning

Process called "classify_argument" that takes arg_type as Integer, convention as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Null type treated as void/no-class
    If arg_type is 0:
        Return ARG_CLASS_NO_CLASS
    End If

    Note: Read the type_kind from the type info structure at offset 0
    Let type_kind be __load(arg_type, 0)

    Note: Type kind 0: Void - no argument class
    If type_kind is 0:
        Return ARG_CLASS_NO_CLASS
    End If

    Note: Type kind 2: Float/Float64 - passed in SIMD/FP registers V0-V7
    If type_kind is 2:
        Return ARG_CLASS_FLOATING
    End If

    Note: Type kind 1: Integer - passed in GPR X0-X7
    If type_kind is 1:
        Return ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
    End If

    Note: Type kind 3: String - passed as pointer in GPR
    If type_kind is 3:
        Return ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
    End If

    Note: Type kind 4: Boolean - passed in GPR (zero-extended to 64 bits)
    If type_kind is 4:
        Return ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
    End If

    Note: All other types (struct pointers, array pointers, reference types,
    Note: optional types, union types, function pointers, etc.) are 8-byte
    Note: pointer values on AArch64 and are passed in general-purpose registers
    Return ARG_CLASS_INTEGER
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Argument Register Mapping
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Maps a function argument (identified by its position within its class) to the physical
register that should hold it, according to AAPCS64.

AAPCS64 argument passing:
  INTEGER class: arg 0->X0(0), 1->X1(1), 2->X2(2), ..., 7->X7(7)
  FLOATING class: arg 0->V0(32), 1->V1(33), 2->V2(34), ..., 7->V7(39)

AAPCS64 tracks integer and floating-point argument indices independently (same as
System V x86_64). The first integer argument always goes in X0 and the first float
argument always goes in V0, regardless of ordering.

Returns the physical register ID, or -1 if the argument must be passed on the stack
because all 8 register slots for that class are exhausted.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_arg_register" that takes convention as Integer, arg_index as Integer, arg_class as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate arg_index is non-negative
    If arg_index is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: NO_CLASS arguments do not occupy a register
    If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_NO_CLASS:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: MEMORY class arguments are explicitly on the stack
    If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_MEMORY:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: AAPCS64 integer argument registers: X0(0) through X7(7)
    If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_INTEGER:
        If arg_index is 0:
            Return 0   Note: X0
        End If
        If arg_index is 1:
            Return 1   Note: X1
        End If
        If arg_index is 2:
            Return 2   Note: X2
        End If
        If arg_index is 3:
            Return 3   Note: X3
        End If
        If arg_index is 4:
            Return 4   Note: X4
        End If
        If arg_index is 5:
            Return 5   Note: X5
        End If
        If arg_index is 6:
            Return 6   Note: X6
        End If
        If arg_index is 7:
            Return 7   Note: X7
        End If
        Note: arg_index >= 8: passed on stack
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: AAPCS64 floating-point argument registers: V0(32) through V7(39)
    If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_FLOATING:
        If arg_index is less than 8:
            Return 32 plus arg_index  Note: V0(32) plus offset
        End If
        Note: arg_index >= 8: passed on stack
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: Unrecognized class falls to stack
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Stack Argument Space Computation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Computes the total stack space (in bytes) required for function arguments that do not
fit into registers under AAPCS64.

AAPCS64 rules:
- Integer arguments beyond the 8th go on the stack
- Float arguments beyond the 8th go on the stack
- Integer and float argument indices are tracked independently
- Each stack argument is naturally aligned (8 bytes for 64-bit values)
- The stack must remain 16-byte aligned at all times

The arg_types parameter is a pointer to an array of type info pointers, and arg_count
is the total number of arguments.
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_stack_args_size" that takes convention as Integer, arg_types as Integer, arg_count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: No arguments means no stack space needed
    If arg_count is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If arg_types is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let stack_bytes be 0

    Note: AAPCS64: integer and float argument indices are independent
    Let int_index be 0
    Let float_index be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count:
        Note: Read the type info pointer for this argument
        Let type_ptr be __load(arg_types, i multiplied by 8)
        Let arg_class be classify_argument(type_ptr, convention)

        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_INTEGER:
            If int_index is greater than or equal to 8:
                Note: This integer argument spills to the stack (8 bytes per slot)
                Set stack_bytes to stack_bytes plus 8
            End If
            Set int_index to int_index plus 1
        End If

        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_FLOATING:
            If float_index is greater than or equal to 8:
                Note: This float argument spills to the stack (8 bytes per slot)
                Set stack_bytes to stack_bytes plus 8
            End If
            Set float_index to float_index plus 1
        End If

        If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_MEMORY:
            Note: Explicitly stack-passed arguments take 8 bytes
            Set stack_bytes to stack_bytes plus 8
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Ensure stack argument area is 16-byte aligned (AAPCS64 requirement)
    Let remainder be stack_bytes modulo 16
    If remainder is not 0:
        Set stack_bytes to stack_bytes plus (16 minus remainder)
    End If

    Return stack_bytes
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Callee-Saved Register List
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns a freshly created List of callee-saved register IDs for AAPCS64.

AAPCS64 callee-saved registers:
  GPRs: X19(19)-X28(28), X29(29)/FP, X30(30)/LR
  FPRs: V8(40)-V15(47) (lower 64 bits, D8-D15, must be preserved)

The list is freshly allocated so the caller can modify it without affecting canonical
convention data. This is important for the register allocator which may filter the list
to only include registers actually used by the function.

Note that X29 (FP) and X30 (LR) are always saved/restored by the prologue/epilogue
using STP/LDP instructions, but they are included in this list for completeness in
register allocation tracking.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_callee_saved_list" that takes convention as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be List.list_create(24)
    If result is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: GPRs: X19-X28 (general-purpose callee-saved)
    List.list_append(result, 19)  Note: X19
    List.list_append(result, 20)  Note: X20
    List.list_append(result, 21)  Note: X21
    List.list_append(result, 22)  Note: X22
    List.list_append(result, 23)  Note: X23
    List.list_append(result, 24)  Note: X24
    List.list_append(result, 25)  Note: X25
    List.list_append(result, 26)  Note: X26
    List.list_append(result, 27)  Note: X27
    List.list_append(result, 28)  Note: X28

    Note: Frame pointer and link register (callee-saved)
    List.list_append(result, 29)  Note: X29 (FP)
    List.list_append(result, 30)  Note: X30 (LR)

    Note: FPRs: V8-V15 (lower 64 bits callee-saved)
    List.list_append(result, 40)  Note: V8 (D8)
    List.list_append(result, 41)  Note: V9 (D9)
    List.list_append(result, 42)  Note: V10 (D10)
    List.list_append(result, 43)  Note: V11 (D11)
    List.list_append(result, 44)  Note: V12 (D12)
    List.list_append(result, 45)  Note: V13 (D13)
    List.list_append(result, 46)  Note: V14 (D14)
    List.list_append(result, 47)  Note: V15 (D15)

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Caller-Saved Register List
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns a freshly created List of caller-saved register IDs for AAPCS64.

AAPCS64 caller-saved (volatile) registers:
  GPRs: X0(0)-X15(15), X16(16)/IP0, X17(17)/IP1, X18(18)/platform
  FPRs: V0(32)-V7(39), V16(48)-V31(63)

These registers may be clobbered by any function call, so the caller must save them
before a call if their values are still needed afterward.

X16 and X17 are intra-procedure-call scratch registers that may be modified by linker
veneers and dynamic linker stubs, so they are always caller-saved.

X18 is platform-dependent: reserved on Darwin (macOS/iOS), available as a temporary on
Linux. We conservatively list it as caller-saved on all platforms.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_caller_saved_list" that takes convention as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be List.list_create(40)
    If result is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: GPRs: X0-X18 are all caller-saved
    List.list_append(result, 0)   Note: X0
    List.list_append(result, 1)   Note: X1
    List.list_append(result, 2)   Note: X2
    List.list_append(result, 3)   Note: X3
    List.list_append(result, 4)   Note: X4
    List.list_append(result, 5)   Note: X5
    List.list_append(result, 6)   Note: X6
    List.list_append(result, 7)   Note: X7
    List.list_append(result, 8)   Note: X8 (indirect result)
    List.list_append(result, 9)   Note: X9
    List.list_append(result, 10)  Note: X10
    List.list_append(result, 11)  Note: X11
    List.list_append(result, 12)  Note: X12
    List.list_append(result, 13)  Note: X13
    List.list_append(result, 14)  Note: X14
    List.list_append(result, 15)  Note: X15
    List.list_append(result, 16)  Note: X16 (IP0)
    List.list_append(result, 17)  Note: X17 (IP1)
    List.list_append(result, 18)  Note: X18 (platform)

    Note: FPRs: V0-V7 and V16-V31 are caller-saved
    List.list_append(result, 32)  Note: V0
    List.list_append(result, 33)  Note: V1
    List.list_append(result, 34)  Note: V2
    List.list_append(result, 35)  Note: V3
    List.list_append(result, 36)  Note: V4
    List.list_append(result, 37)  Note: V5
    List.list_append(result, 38)  Note: V6
    List.list_append(result, 39)  Note: V7
    List.list_append(result, 48)  Note: V16
    List.list_append(result, 49)  Note: V17
    List.list_append(result, 50)  Note: V18
    List.list_append(result, 51)  Note: V19
    List.list_append(result, 52)  Note: V20
    List.list_append(result, 53)  Note: V21
    List.list_append(result, 54)  Note: V22
    List.list_append(result, 55)  Note: V23
    List.list_append(result, 56)  Note: V24
    List.list_append(result, 57)  Note: V25
    List.list_append(result, 58)  Note: V26
    List.list_append(result, 59)  Note: V27
    List.list_append(result, 60)  Note: V28
    List.list_append(result, 61)  Note: V29
    List.list_append(result, 62)  Note: V30
    List.list_append(result, 63)  Note: V31

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Stack Frame Adjustment Computation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Computes the total frame size ensuring the stack remains 16-byte aligned under AAPCS64.

AAPCS64 mandates that the stack pointer (SP) must be 16-byte aligned at all times when
accessing memory through SP. This is stricter than x86_64 which only requires alignment
at the CALL instruction boundary. AArch64 hardware enforces this with alignment faults.

The typical AArch64 prologue is:
  stp x29, x30, [sp, #-frame_size]!   -> Pre-decrement SP, save FP and LR
  mov x29, sp                          -> Set new frame pointer
  stp x19, x20, [sp, #offset]         -> Save callee-saved registers
  ...more callee-saved pairs...

The frame_size in the STP instruction must include space for:
1. Saved FP and LR (16 bytes, always first - handled by STP x29,x30)
2. Callee-saved register pairs (each STP saves 16 bytes)
3. Local variable space (local_size bytes)
4. Outgoing argument spill area

The total frame_size must be a multiple of 16 for SP alignment.

Parameters:
- convention: the calling convention ID (for future per-convention adjustments)
- local_size: bytes needed for local variables
- callee_saved_count: number of callee-saved registers to push (not counting FP/LR)

Returns the computed frame size in bytes, guaranteed to be a multiple of 16.
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_frame_adjustment" that takes convention as Integer, local_size as Integer, callee_saved_count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: FP (X29) and LR (X30) are always saved as a pair = 16 bytes
    Let fp_lr_size be 16

    Note: Callee-saved registers are saved in pairs using STP instructions
    Note: Each pair occupies 16 bytes. If count is odd, one register is saved
    Note: alone but still takes 8 bytes; we round up to pairs for alignment.
    Let callee_pairs be callee_saved_count divided by 2
    Let callee_remainder be callee_saved_count modulo 2
    Let callee_save_size be callee_pairs multiplied by 16
    If callee_remainder is not 0:
        Note: Odd register count: the unpaired register still takes 8 bytes,
        Note: but we must maintain 16-byte alignment, so we pad to 16
        Set callee_save_size to callee_save_size plus 16
    End If

    Note: Total frame size = FP/LR + callee saves + locals
    Let frame_size be fp_lr_size plus callee_save_size plus local_size

    Note: Round up to 16-byte alignment (AAPCS64 mandatory)
    Let remainder be frame_size modulo 16
    If remainder is not 0:
        Set frame_size to frame_size plus (16 minus remainder)
    End If

    Return frame_size
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Callee-Saved Register Query
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Determines whether a given physical register is callee-saved under AAPCS64.
Returns 1 if the register must be preserved by the callee, 0 if it is caller-saved.

AAPCS64 callee-saved:
  GPRs: X19(19)-X28(28), X29(29)/FP, X30(30)/LR
  FPRs: V8(40)-V15(47) (lower 64 bits only)

SP(31) is always preserved but handled separately by frame management.
XZR(65) is a constant zero register and has no save/restore semantics.
@End Reasoning

Process called "is_callee_saved" that takes convention as Integer, reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SP is always preserved but managed by prologue/epilogue, not listed as callee-saved
    If reg_id is 31:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: XZR is not a real register
    If reg_id is 65:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: GPR callee-saved range: X19(19) through X28(28)
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 19:
        If reg_id is less than or equal to 28:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: X29 (FP) is callee-saved
    If reg_id is 29:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: X30 (LR) is callee-saved
    If reg_id is 30:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: FPR callee-saved range: V8(40) through V15(47)
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 40:
        If reg_id is less than or equal to 47:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: All other registers (X0-X18, V0-V7, V16-V31) are caller-saved
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Convention Selection Helper
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns a CallingConventionInfo for AArch64. All AArch64 platforms use AAPCS64 as the
standard calling convention. The target_os parameter controls platform-specific details
like red zone size (128 on Darwin, 0 on Linux).

Windows on ARM64 uses a slight variation of AAPCS64 but the register assignments are
identical. The main difference is that X18 is reserved as the TEB pointer on Windows,
which is handled by not allocating X18 for general use.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_convention_for_target" that takes target_os as Integer returns Integer:
    Return create_aapcs64_convention(target_os)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Return Register Selection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the physical register ID for the function return value based on the type
classification under AAPCS64.

AAPCS64:
  Integer/pointer returns: X0 (register ID 0)
  Float/double returns: V0/D0/S0 (register ID 32)

For small struct returns (up to 16 bytes), X0 and X1 are used together. For larger
struct returns, the caller passes a pointer in X8 (indirect result location register).
This function handles the simple scalar case.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_return_register" that takes convention as Integer, return_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let arg_class be classify_argument(return_type, convention)

    If arg_class is ARG_CLASS_FLOATING:
        Return 32  Note: V0 for float returns
    End If

    Note: INTEGER, MEMORY, NO_CLASS all return via X0
    Return 0  Note: X0 for integer/pointer returns
End Process
